%BOM---------------------
Date:5/2/2008 10:56:26 AM
From:Paul Senior
Madharry, I wouldn't purchase any shares of such a fund as you mentioned
without knowing more about it. Such as:

What focused sector it is in, and how much confidence I have in that particular
sector and how weighted I already am in such stocks.

What the history of the discount to nav is. 25% percent seems like a lot.
Apparently the fund always trades at a discount to its nav. I presume that is
why management has decided or is pressured to buy back shares (to close the
gap).

What the fund pays in terms of dividend and yield. What the yield is -- how
high or low it is. What the dividend is composed of -- pass through of
dividends from the underlying stocks and/or some component of 'return of
capital'? How the dividend might be enhanced, i.e. does the fund use leverage
to enhance yield. (I've got burned on more than one of these types-- dividend
yield on fund much higher than any individual stock in the fund -- subsequently
the fund announces it's apparently somewhat trapped in the "auction rate
preferred securities market" -- monies borrowed to leverage the fund).

Jmo.
